text.text:
You were all talk about having a quiet weekend, but your one bevvy has turned into three large ones and they've sent you over the edge into a boogie craze. That's right, you need to get your stamps on to a D-floor, sharpish, preferably in a welcoming spot where no-one gives a frick about your knowledge of techno or your lack of side bag filled with party favours.

East London, as it turns out, has a lot of that to offer. From inclusive dance-floors playing soulful tunes to live music and heartfelt karaoke, here's a few places to try before you reluctantly end up at The Dolphin.

tip.text:
Moth Club - short 'of course' for The Memorable Order of Tin Hats - is a wondrously kitsch time warp of a boozer and event space. It’s a glittery mash-up of two cultural scenes colliding: an ex-servicemen’s club whose members still shoot the shit and play darts in the old bar whilst a sprightly and unsightly blend of Hackney young’uns come and embrace a lil' joyous abandon.

Nice indie gigs, 80s nights, bingo, themed quizzes (Peep Show, Ru Paul, Simpsons...) and film screenings take place under the gold glittered ceiling, amid red velvet booths and the iconic red and black chequered floor. Yep it's got the aesthetic, but it's also got the kind of welcoming vibe that’ll have you spinning around to Abba at midnight without a care in the goddamn world.

tip.text:
There’s nowhere quite like Bethnal Green Working Men’s Club. Sitting proudly in the East End since 1887, this boozer and good-time haunt seems to exist in a glorious time warp: with carpeted floors straight outta the 60s, kitsch decor and £4 pints; and not a craft beer or organic wine in sight.

It’s about as welcoming, inclusive and unpretentious a night-time spot as you could hope to find - the moment you cross the threshold all concerns about steeze and style float away with the spirit of burlesque, 90s parties, comedy, drag, karaoke nights and everything that falls in the gaps taking their place. Add in one of the friendliest crowds around and you've got a memorable, endearingly ramshackle place that pops off in a wild and wonderful way.

Drinks are cheap, floors are carpeted and outfits are kitsch.

tip.text:
If this place could talk, it would have quite some tales to tell. It's a scruffy, ramshackle late-night haunt where you'll probably only find yourself past midnight in desperate need of a place to shake it. And it can really kick, spilling out into the streets; the reason behind many a sore head.

If you do come earlier in the evening you'll find talented jazz musicians flexing their throats and thumbs and a menu of meaty obscure oddities: crocodile, jerk rabbit, ostrich fillet, grilled zebra. Frankly we don't know what to say - we haven't sampled it and we don't know where they're sourcing it from. Instead, stick to what this place does best: late night thrills and Dalston debauchery.

tip.text:
Like your mum at a wedding, The Shacklewell Arms is a beautiful, sweaty mess - and we love her for it. From peeling astroturf in the graffitied garden and dripping taps in the rank toilets; to the noisy pub in the front and the humid, low-ceilinged event space in the back, the place exudes scruffy charm with only the smallest helping of pretension. It rocks and it rolls and occasionally it does both at once.

It’s run by the minds that bring us Field Day every year, so you’ll often catch up-and-coming acts that, in a couple of years when they blow, you can say you saw in a dingy Hackney pub - which is just the boost your rapidly dwindling stock of social capital could use.

tip.text:
This is an endangered species: a characterful anachronism of an East End boozer that property developers have, predictably, been sniffing around for some time. We can only hope that the owner, Pauline, and the pub's patrons keep fighting the good fight because this is a community cornerstone with history, heritage and soul.

A 700-year-old tavern that Dickens, Chaucer and Pepys wrote about, its more recent use has been as an arts and music events space where big acts (Nick Cave, John Cooper Clarke, Anna Calvi) have dropped in to create sweaty and raucous gigs. With its battered but beautiful interior, it's also become a big hit for film producers and regularly acts as the setting in period pieces. What a nice place to sink a pint and catch a performance.

tip.text:
*Closed 02/19*

Sick of enduring crap East London clubnights, the squad behind Emily's gave themselves the challenge of doing better. Looking to deliver a cracking night out, this may just be the perfect spot to get a little loose.

Decor is just as rough and ready as your outfit but nobody cares cause the vibes are fierce - especially at Italo night. Cocktails are named after celebs and their drinking scandals. Go for a Graham Norton and down a Sauvigon Blanc; grab a long island ice tea, Britney-style; or get Riri wasted with rum, ginger beer and bitters.

Free before 11pm, £5 after.

tip.text: Located on Ridley Road Market, this tropical dance box is the place to wear whatever the hell you want and dance however the hell you like. If you can't vogue like Madonna on this 80s-style dance-floor, then when can you? Once at the bar, get your hands on a Ginger Mojito, because big cocktails are better than little ones and because Ginger Mojitos are even tastier than they sound and at £5 you surely can't go wrong. Bear in mind, this place is completely cash-free so bring your card and leave your penny jar at home.

tip.text:
Sweetie, darling, stop flouncing around shitty pubs and head over to Haggerston. The Glory may look like your average East End boozer, complete with an ebony bar, friendly wine-drinkers and chilled-out tuneage, but once you make your way downstairs, it's an entirely different picture.

Expect to see the Glory's infamous co-owners, John Sizzle and Jonny Woo, grace the basement's stage with their presence, along with a plethora of London's alternative cabaret performers, camp DJs, thought-provoking pieces and outlandish performance artists. The Glory wanted to forge a home for London's incredibly diverse and talented queer counterculture, and they've done a damn good job of it.

tip.text:
Found down a narrow-ish street amongst the bustle of Hackney lies The Gun, everything you want your local boozer to be and more. In some form or another the pub itself has been serving pints of the good stuff for Hackney patrons since 1860, but in its latest guise The Gun offers hearty food, locally sourced ales and spirits, arguably the city's greatest pub quiz, and some of the best pub dogs to stroke in all of LDN.

They also welcome a weekly rotation of some of London's finest DJ talent all in the confines of a cozy east end drinkery; with DJs spinning from Thursday to Sunday and dancing heavily encouraged. From tropical disco for your end of week celebration to Sunday selections to calm your soul, The Gun offers a night on the tiles without taking a big knock to your bank balance.

Add DJs spinning from Thursday to Sunday - tropical disco for your end of week celebration to Sunday selections to calm your soul - and you've a night on the tiles that won't knock your bank balance too hard.

tip.text:
If there ever was a basement that feels nothing like a basement, but really is just a basement, it'd be VFD. There are no decorations to speak of, the loos have swinging doors and no locks, the bar is big enough for three skinny bartenders and the dance floor can fit maybe 40 people, tops. It's grimy, it's sweaty, and yet it's so much fun.

This alternative basement plays host to some of the quirkiest nights, with everything from die-ins, spiritual rituals, spoken word nights, drag acts, erotic salons and cool pop-electro-camp-tastic club nights like Sassitude, Dirty Diana or Straight Nasty. It's pretty hit and miss at times, but it's so intimate that you can't help but have a good time.

Be warned: VFD only opens when it has an event going on, so double check before heading there.
